The « Green Deal » European
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The « European Green Deal » announced by the European Commission is so far the first global sustainable development plan decided by a major world region.
It thus becomes a benchmark for the entire world – a guide to the transformation towards a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, a first agenda for all to achieve this.
Naturally, the task ahead for Europeans is daunting.
Even the reading of the documents that have just been made public is: a veritable feast at first glance of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of subjects involved and related, ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its detractors will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense: it is rational.
The sustainable development goals are clearly stated, targets are defined based on objectives submitted to a time frame, and programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the declared ambition is to achieve carbon neutrality (net zero greenhouse gas emissions) by 2050, to implement a circular economy that puts an end to destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, and to establish a food system "from farm to table" that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed products by industry, nor the earth with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on citizens themselves.
Again, critics will see announcements of public consultations as mere show for empty talk.
But try telling them about useless chatter to the French President Emmanuel Macron, who has been facing protests turning into riots for over a year, or to the Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly rose up this fall after a slight increase in metro ticket prices.
Both Macron and Piñera are convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed their countries to carbon neutrality by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to organize or structure a public consultation, but after the fact.
American neoliberals will once again roll their eyes and claim that the "market" will know how to address climate change.
But just look at the United States today.
If neoliberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have reason to worry.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means having to deal with elevators, broken escalators, malfunctioning shuttles, taxis that don't arrive, non-existent train connections, highways in such poor condition that they can't be used, replaced by detours.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American electoral cycle costs today 8 billion dollars, if not more, and the financing is ensured by billionaires, major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and interest groups resolved to lower taxes and at all costs protect the status quo.
The market solutions are a joke when politics is subject to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal shows what a government should be like and not one subordinate to corporate interests.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense and not narrowly partisan).
An mixed economy, which combines markets, state regulatory power, public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions grounded in public-private partnerships, and an informed populace.
In fact, it is the most sophisticated level of industrial policy.
(I recently outlined, in broad terms, what a social democratic Green New Deal for the United States would look like.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most crucial point is that the advanced technologies necessary to create an advanced, decarbonized, resource-efficient, and thus ecologically sustainable economy exist, at either the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and collaborative economies in transportation or other infrastructure, we can decarbonize the energy system, move to a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows.
But this requires overcoming three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
Larger oil companies will need to absorb losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining, and other public aids.
The European plan rightly claims a "just transition."
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, as of course other world regions, will need to realign a relatively small portion of its production, around 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, particularly for new infrastructure, public procurement, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, and so on. The funding will come from the private sector, but also from public budgets.
Europe must confront ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
Facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
The European Union represents about 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China accounts for 30% and the United States for 14%.
Even if the EU manages to fully implement its green deal, it will be in vain if other world regions do not join in the fight.
European leaders rightly consider that diplomacy is fundamental to the success of the green deal.
Let's take China as an example.
After decades of rapid growth that eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest CO2 emitter (although its per capita emissions remain half those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of the global climate.
On one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if they do not make sufficient efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must confront the dangers of the unintended cold war launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist, under pressure from the United States, decarbonization, especially since Trump rejects it himself.
European diplomacy could make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's sneaky measures to undermine China and instead offers China a clear and positive partnership: working together to establish sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to Europe's.
Such a partnership would be immensely beneficial for Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that separate them, let alone the world as a whole.
The Europe has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
